âœ… Input Grid Example:
int[][] grid = {
    {0, 0, 0},
    {0, 1, 0},
    {0, 0, 0}
};
This is a 3x3 grid, where:

0 â†’ allowed cell

1 â†’ blocked cell

We can move only right or down

Start from (0,0) â†’ end at (2,2)

ğŸ‘€ Visual Representation:
(0,0) (0,1) (0,2)
(1,0) (1,1) (1,2)
(2,0) (2,1) (2,2)
ğŸ§  Objective:
Count all valid paths from (0,0) to (2,2) avoiding blocked cells.

âœ… Step-by-Step Dry Run:
1. Call: solve(0,0)
grid[0][0] == 0 â†’ OK

not destination â†’ go right and down

2. Call: solve(0,1)
grid[0][1] == 0

Not destination â†’ right & down

3. Call: solve(0,2)
grid[0][2] == 0

Not destination â†’ right & down

4. Call: solve(0,3) â†’ âŒ Out of bounds â†’ returns 0
5. Call: solve(1,2)
grid[1][2] == 0

Go right & down

6. Call: solve(1,3) â†’ âŒ returns 0
7. Call: solve(2,2) âœ… Reached destination â†’ returns 1
â†’ So solve(1,2) = 1
â†’ So solve(0,2) = 1

8. Back to solve(0,1), now try solve(1,1)
grid[1][1] == 1 âŒ blocked â†’ return 0
â†’ So solve(0,1) = right(1) + down(0) = 1

9. Back to solve(0,0), now do solve(1,0)
grid[1][0] == 0

10. solve(1,1) â†’ âŒ blocked â†’ return 0
11. solve(2,0) â†’ ok
12. solve(2,1) â†’ ok
13. solve(2,2) â†’ âœ… destination â†’ return 1
â†’ solve(2,1) = right(1) + down(0) = 1
â†’ solve(2,0) = right(1) + down(0) = 1
â†’ solve(1,0) = right(0) + down(1) = 1

ğŸ” Final Calculation:
solve(0,0) = right (1) + down (1) = 2
âœ… Final Answer: 2
So, there are 2 unique paths from top-left to bottom-right avoiding the blocked cell.

ğŸ“ Summary of Memo Table (visited[][]):
Cell	    Value (Ways)
(2,2)	        1
(2,1)	        1
(2,0)	        1
(1,2)	        1
(1,0)	        1
(0,2)	        1
(0,1)	        1
(0,0)	        2 (Final ans)
